
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"] # this is a list of fruits, it is a collection of items that are ordered and changeable. Lists are written with square brackets [] and the items are separated by commas.
x, y, z = fruits # this is called unpacking a list, it allows you to assign the values of a list to multiple variables in a single line. In this case, x will be assigned the value "apple", y will be assigned the value "banana", and z will be assigned the value "cherry". The number of variables on the left side of the assignment must match the number of items in the list on the right side, otherwise you will get a ValueError.
print(x) # it will print "apple" because x is assigned the value "apple" from the fruits list.
print(y)# it will print "banana" because y is assigned the value "banana" from the fruits list.
print(z) # it will print "cherry" because z is assigned the value "cherry" from the fruits list.